  <title xml:lang="EN">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Save the Children/Syrian refugees in Iraq, 2013</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2" xml:lang="EN">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The conflict in Syria has been escalating since early 2011 and particular since the spring 2012 a steadily increasing number of people have been seeking refuge in neighboring counties. The significant caseload of refugees coming to Iraq has resulted in largely overburdening infrastructure, limiting access to basic services and a large number of vulnerable children and families were not receiving any support. Providing for the immediate relief and tending to their physical and psychosocial wellbeing was thus the overriding priority for this project. In total, 8760 families have benefitted from Non-Food Items (hygiene kits) distribution. Standard Hygiene Kit content included detergent (for clothes), dishwashing liquid, shampoo, sanitary pads, bar soap, garbage bags and a plastic zipper bag. 

The project also provided safe spaces and structured activities to support the coping and psychosocial wellbeing of the wider group of children target through this program. 2960 children were registered and regularly participated in Child Friendly Space activities in the two project locations (Erbil and Dohuk Governorates). At the same time, the project also strengthened the referral mechanisms and engaged the communities on child protection concerns to ensure that children at serious risk were detected and protected. 

To respond to the immense psychosocial needs of children affected by conflict this project also included a child resilience intervention that have been designed to strengthen children&#xBF;s capacity to cope with trauma and has been shown to positively impact on their engagement and performance at school, improve social relations, and to reduce incidences of conflict. 350 children attended sessions on a regular basis through the child resilience program. The project achieved the expected results.</narrative>
  </description>
